06535nam a22009135i 9783110688719DE-B159720210421021438.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210421t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020951273  a97831106887197 a10.1515/97831106887192doi  a(DE-B1597)541625  a(OCoLC)1243311499  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0200002bisacsh00aPoetic Critique :bEncounters with Art and Literature /cMichel Chaouli, Jan Lietz, Jutta Müller-Tamm, Simon Schleusener. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VIII, 204 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWeltLiteraturen / World Literatures ;v1900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tWhat Is Poetic Critique? -- tWhy Adding 'Poetic' to 'Critique' Adds Nothing to Critique -- tSchlegel's Words, Rightly Used -- tStorytelling and Forgetfulness -- tPoetry, Critique, Imitation -- t"Echo Reconciles" -- tOn Not Forcing the Question: Criticism and Playing Along -- tLa Chambre Poétique -- tThe Silence of the Concepts (in Meillassoux's After Finitude and Gottlob Frege) -- tTheater as Critical Praxis: Interruption and Citability -- tHistoricism's Forms: The Aesthetics of Critique -- tPoetic Criticism and the Work of Fiction: Goethe, Joyce, and Coetzee -- tSurface, Distance, Depth: The Text and its Outside -- tContributors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aPoetic critique - is that not an oxymoron? Do these two forms of behavior, the poetic and the critical, not pull in different, even opposite, directions? For many scholars working in the humanities today, they largely do, but that has not always been the case. Friedrich Schlegel, for one, believed that critique worthy of its name must itself be poetic. Only then would it stand a chance of responding adequately to the work of art. Taking Schlegel's idea of poetische Kritik as a starting point, this volume reflects on the possibility of drawing these alleged opposites closer together. In light of current debates about the legacy of critique, it investigates whether a concept such as poetic critique (or poetic criticism) lends itself to enriching our intellectual practice by engaging with the poetic potential of criticism and the critical value of art and literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aCritique and Postcritique.  aFriedrich Schlegel.  aLiterary Theory and Aesthetics.  aPoetic Critique.  aliterary theorie.1 aAshton, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaouli, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaouli, Michel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChaudhuri, Amit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolven, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDüttmann, Alexander García, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElmer, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEusterschulte, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKates, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLietz, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLietz, Jan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMenke, Bettine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichaels, Walter Benn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat